<TITLE> European shares drop after weak US jobs data </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Jan 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares fell on Friday after data showed the US economy generated far fewer jobs than expected in December and the unemployment rate hit a two-year high, raising the chances of another rate cut as growth slows. The US government said 18,000 workers had been added to non-farm payrolls last month, compared with forecasts for a rise of 70,000, and compared with an upwardly revised 115,000 rise in November. The national unemployment rate rose to 5 percent, its highest since November 2005. Banks were the worst performing sector. Shares in UBS fell 1.9 percent, Banco Santander fell 1 percent and Credit Suisse shed 1.7 percent. By 1336 GMT the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares was down 0.5 percent at 1,476.86 points, compared with a 0.2-percent gain just before the payrolls figure. The index was also down from the session high of 1,476.72, which marked a 0.5-percent gain on the day. US stock futures reversed gains and fell between 0.7 and 1.3 percent indicating a weak open on Wall Street. Around Europe, London's FTSE 100 index lost 0.4 percent, while Frankfurt's DAX fell 0.8 percent and Paris' CAC 40 shed 0.7 perce
